column28:
The possible mechanics of interaction consist in:
- grasping the dishes;
- moving the dishes;
- raising the dishes to users’ ears.
Typically users move near the table, grasp and move the dishes and listen to the stories, possibly talking among them and commenting on what listened. In facts it is possible (and wished by the design team) that multiple users interact simultaneously with the exhibit.

column30:
With a variety of sensors and microelectronics, each module oﬀers the ability to calculate, behave and narrate according to our wishes. The Signiﬁcant capability however is the human being, carrying the device.
The final aim of the digital supported experience is to create an involving experience for users which makes them participants of a sort of collective ritual. In this context digital technology plays a key role when it allows to:
1) orally quote stories of people interviewed about rituals, making their accounts more vivid;
2) make the four rituals interact, thus creating a new ritual in which particular words and stories are linked to certain movements of the dishes.
Other interesting features are:
- the kind of qualitative research done to represent cultures and rituals;
- the creative use of the outcomes of the qualitative research in the installation;
- the idea that contents change depending on the mechanics of interaction of users.

